##Drawdown

01_Why drawdown must be calculated on wealth, not raw returns
Beacuse you need a series of peaks, raw returns doesn't give you that
Drawdown measures peak-to-trough loss relative to accumulated value, which requires compounding returns into a wealth path. Raw returns are period-to-period changes with no memory of prior levels — you can't identify "how far below the peak am I" without first reconstructing the cumulative wealth series that returns compound into.

02_How missing dividend adjustments distort drawdown
If dividends aren't reinvested into the wealth series (i.e., you use raw/unadjusted price instead of total return), the wealth path drops mechanically on ex-dividend dates without any real economic loss — this creates phantom, small drawdowns that don't reflect true investor loss. Worse, over long horizons the unadjusted price will systematically understate the running peak, making historical MDD look larger (or recovery periods longer) than the actual total-return experience.

03_Explain how drawdown helps evaluate strategy survivability.
Strategy survivability depends on capital, margin, psychology, and mandate constraints.

